      <hedline>
        <hl1>Bush vs. Gore, Round 1: Now the People Debate; Unfair to Nader</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Katherine Howe letter, commenting on presidential debate, scores exclusion of third-party candidate Ralph Nader</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I find it unconscionable that Ralph Nader was not allowed to take part in the debate in Boston on Tuesday evening (front page, Oct. 4). Some polls show Mr. Nader with a 5 percent approval rating, with even higher ratings in many states. Clearly, he represents a point of view held by many Americans, a point of view that is being unjustly silenced.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I find it unconscionable that Ralph Nader was not allowed to take part in the debate in Boston on Tuesday evening (front page, Oct. 4). Some polls show Mr. Nader with a 5 percent approval rating, with even higher ratings in many states. Clearly, he represents a point of view held by many Americans, a point of view that is being unjustly silenced.</p>
        <p>No wonder so many of us feel as if participatory politics isn't worth the time and effort. Closed debates only serve to underline the impression that American politics are for the select, dominant few. Open the debates to alternate candidates, or change the word from ''democracy'' to ''oligarchy.''</p>
        <p>KATHERINE HOWE  New York, Oct. 4, 2000</p>
      </block>
